    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay thanks. i've noticed my lights flicker a bit when i'm idling at a stoplight. is that definitely the alternator or could it be something else causing those weird electrical glitches?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Flickering lights at a stoplight are a classic sign of an alternator struggling to keep up, but they can also be caused by a loose battery cable or a failing starter motor!\n\nThink of the alternator as a tire pump that's running out of air; if it's not pumping fast enough, your lights will dim or flicker like a candle in a drafty room. If the alternator is the only thing failing, you might also notice the battery light staying on even when the engine is running, or the radio acting up with static noise.\n\nHowever, if the lights flicker *only* when you're idling and then stay steady once you move, it could be a loose battery cable or a bad starter motor trying to crank the engine too hard! It's like trying to push a heavy door with one hand while the other hand is holding the handle; if the door wobbles, it's not the door itself, but the way you're pushing it!\n\nIf the flickering gets worse as you drive, it's definitely the alternator, but if it's just a one-time glitch, it might be a loose connection. You should probably check the battery cables next, as they are often the",
